# 2. 落書きだらけのストリート

Male Teacher: Let's see. Ms. Azusawa, would you solve this problem for us?
Kohane: Oh, o-okay... Um, I...
Male Teacher: Not sure, huh?
Kohane: No, you, uh...square the three and...
Male Teacher: How about you, Ms. Sato?
Kohane: Oh...
Minori: That was rude. They could have given you a little more time! You knew the answer, didn't you?
Kohane: Y-Yeah... But it's okay. It's my fault for not speaking up...
Kohane: (Even though I'm in high school now, I haven't changed a bit.)
Minori: Oh, look at the time! I've got to get to dance practice! See you tomorrow, Kohane!
Kohane: Yeah. See you tomorrow, Minori.
Kohane: (Minori sure is amazing. She's working so hard to achieve her dream of becoming an idol.)
Kohane: (I still can't remember it very well, but that dream I had the other day gave me the feeling something was about to change.)
Kohane: (I wonder if I'd be able to change if I found a dream or a goal to reach for like Minori.)
Kohane: Oh, Mom's texting me. Hm? <Could you buy that CD for me on your way home?>
Kohane: She must be talking about that new album she mentioned the other day. <Okay, will do.>
Kohane: (It's been a while since I was in a CD shop.)
Kohane: (Oh, they're playing that new Miku single. It sounds so cool. I wonder who wrote it.)
Kohane: Hm? It should be around here somewhere. Excuse me, do you have this CD?
Shop Clerk: Oh, I'm very sorry, but we're currently sold out of that particular album. Our alley shop still has a few copies, though.
Kohane: (The alley shop? Isn't that the one in that scary-looking back alley?)
Shop Clerk: If you'd like, I can call and have them reserve a copy for you.
Kohane: (I'd rather not go down that street, but Mom was really looking forward to this.)
Kohane: Th-Thank you. I'll head over there now.
Shop Clerk: Come again!
Kohane: Phew... I'm glad I found a copy...
Kohane: This area really does have a spooky feel to it, though. Why are all the walls covered in graffiti?
Kohane: The map on my phone says the station is back this way...
Kohane: H-Huh? This street doesn't look familiar.
Kohane: Where am I? Oh no! My phone just died!
Kohane: It won't turn back on! What am I going to do... I-I'll have to ask someone for directions...
Passerby A: Ahahahaha! What are you talking about?! You're so full of yourself!
Kohane: U-Um, excuse me...
Passerby B: Hey, what do you say we stay out all night?!
Kohane: Oh... Wh-What should I do...
Kohane: I don't recognize this street either. A-And it's starting to get dark...
Kohane: (Why am I always like this? I don't even have the courage to ask someone for directions...)
Kohane: (I can't deal with something like this...)
???: ——♪ ——♪
Kohane: Hm? Is that...music?
???: ——♪ ——♪
Kohane: It's coming from over there.
Kohane: Weekend Garage? It says they're open. I wonder what kind of place it is.
Kohane: Oh, maybe someone who works there can give me directions. But that would mean going into a shop I've never been to before...
Kohane: At this rate, though, it's going to get dark soon. I-I'll have to try it...
???: Yeah, that's great! You guys sound even better than usual!
DJ: That's because you're here to help, An! Are you sure you don't want to team up with us and put on some shows?
An: Hm... I'll think about it.
Musician A: Hahaha! Rejected again! All right, now that we're warmed up, let's move on to the next set. Since there's three of us, how about a mic relay?
An: Got it! I'm going to freestyle a little, then!
Kohane: U-Um, excuse me...
An: ♪——!
Kohane: !!
An: ♪!!!
Kohane: (What's...this...?)
Kohane: (My ears feel like they're ringing, but...)
Kohane: Amazing... They're so cool!
An: Man, that was great! Thanks, everyone!
Musician B: Man, you're starting to make us look bad. You've been practicing again, haven't you?
An: Thanks, but I still have a long way to go. I want to become even better than I am now.
An: Then I'm going to put on a show that'll be even greater than RAD WEEKEND!
DJ: Better than that?! Dreamin' big again, I see!
Kohane: (It sounds like she has some kind of dream.)
Kohane: (I bet that's why she looks so cool while she's singing.)
Musician B: I bet you feel pretty proud to have a daughter who wants to follow in your footsteps, don't you Ken?
An's Father: Sure do. It's a bit strange, though. I didn't teach her a thing.
An: I can't very well sit around twiddling my thumbs after seeing a show like yours, Dad.
An: Just you wait! I swear I'll surpass you one of these days!
An's Father: I'm looking forward to it. Before you go showing up your old man, though, how about you take that table their order?
An: I'm on it! You might try to treat your employees a bit nicer, though. Oh? A customer?
Kohane: Ah!
An: Sorry about that. I was so absorbed with my singing that I didn't see you there! Here, this seat over here is open.
Kohane: Ah... I-I, uh... Um... I-I'm sorry!
An: Huh? O-Oh, wait! She left...
An: I feel like I've seen her before, though. Maybe at a show somewhere?
Kohane: Huff... Huff... Huff... Huff...
Kohane: (I ran away... And after she was nice enough to talk to me, too...)
Kohane: (But... What's going on? What is this feeling?)
Kohane: My heart is racing!
